        heading: "What's Actually Happening to Your Headlights",
        content: `Modern headlight lenses are made of polycarbonate — a lightweight plastic that's significantly cheaper and safer than glass. Polycarbonate has one real weakness: it degrades under UV radiation. Every manufacturer applies a factory UV-resistant clear coat when the lens is made, but that coating is thin and wears through within five to eight years of sun exposure.

Once the clear coat is gone, UV rays attack the polycarbonate directly. The surface oxidizes at a molecular level — the polymer chains break down and scatter light instead of transmitting it. What you see as "haze" is actually thousands of micro-fractures and oxidized surface particles. The lens isn't dirty. It's structurally degraded at the surface layer.

That's why an auto headlight cleaner spray or a wipe-down with any headlight car cleaner product does almost nothing. You're not removing contamination — you're trying to reverse chemistry with a cloth. It doesn't work.`,
